";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:642:\"<p>Are wondering how to use nonprofit WordPress forms to help your cause? Besides simply asking people for money, there are other ways to take advantage of WPForms’ nonprofit form templates. In this article, we’ll outline the different ways you can use nonprofit WordPress forms to help your organization thrive. 1. Online Donations Though creating an [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/unique-ways-to-use-nonprofit-wordpress-forms-to-help-your-cause/\">4 Unique Ways to Use Nonprofit WordPress Forms to Help Your Cause</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:14:\"Lindsay Liedke\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:10053:\"<p>Are wondering how to use nonprofit WordPress forms to help your cause? Besides simply asking people for money, there are other ways to take advantage of WPForms’ nonprofit form templates.</p>\n<p>In this article, we’ll outline the different ways you can use nonprofit WordPress forms to help your organization thrive.</p>\n<h3>1. Online Donations</h3>\n<p>Though creating an online donation form is the most obvious use for a nonprofit donation form, it would be wrong to not include it in our roundup. After all, if you’re trying to <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/online-fundraising-ideas-for-nonprofits/\">raise money for your nonprofit organization</a>, like Mozilla , creating a simple online donation form is the quickest and easiest way.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-273283\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/mozilla-donation-page.png\" alt=\"mozilla donation page\" width=\"562\" height=\"344\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/mozilla-donation-page.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/mozilla-donation-page-300x184.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Plus, WPForms has some neat features that help <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/6-tactics-to-boost-donation-form-conversions/\">boost your donation form conversions</a> and generate you more money.</p>\n<p>Collecting money from donors is what’s going to keep your nonprofit alive. Luckily, WPForms makes collecting donations from people, using <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/paypal-standard-addon/\">PayPal</a> or <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/stripe-addon/\">Stripe</a>, very simple.</p>\n<p>Even more exciting, our Stripe addon now has recurring payment capability so people that want to donate to your cause on a regular basis can just by filling out your donation form with their payment information.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-261830\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/enable-recurring-payments.png\" alt=\"enable recurring payments\" width=\"562\" height=\"390\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/enable-recurring-payments.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/enable-recurring-payments-300x208.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>For help with setting up Stripe recurring, check out our documentation on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-install-and-use-the-stripe-addon-with-wpforms/\">how to install and use the Stripe addon</a>.</p>\n<p>Here you’ll learn how to connect Stripe to your online donation form, add Stripe to your forms, enable recurring payments, and even set up smart conditional logic to make your donation forms more dynamic.</p>\n<h3>2. Volunteer Sign-Ups</h3>\n<p>When you stop and think about it, volunteers are what help your nonprofit organization carry out its mission.</p>\n<p>For instance, your organization may put on events like:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Charity Auctions</li>\n<li>Sports Tournaments</li>\n<li>Walk/Run Race Events</li>\n<li>School-Wide Yard Sales</li>\n<li>Alumni Networking Dinners</li>\n<li>Holiday Gift Wrapping Services</li>\n<li>Community Bake Sales</li>\n<li>And so much more</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The thing is, in order for these types of events to run smoothly and generate the most money possible, either through event participation or donor sponsors, you’ll need a reliable crew of volunteers to help.</p>\n<p>Volunteers are vital for the before, during, and after of any nonprofit event. That’s why <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-set-up-a-volunteer-application-form-in-wordpress/\">creating a volunteer application form</a> on your website to get people to say they’ll help is so useful.</p>\n<p>For an example, take a look at the Sundance Festival’s volunteer application form:</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-273287\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/volunteer-form-example.png\" alt=\"volunteer form example\" width=\"562\" height=\"688\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/volunteer-form-example.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/volunteer-form-example-245x300.png 245w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Your website reaches far and wide. Events that you’re hosting will spread throughout the community and those that want to get involved will be able to sign up easily on your site using your volunteer form.</p>\n<p>And don’t forget, <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-send-wpforms-entries-to-google-calendar\">WPForms integrates easily with Google Calendar</a> using our <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/zapier-addon/\">Zapier addon</a> so anytime someone agrees to volunteer for an event you’re hosting, the form entry will be sent directly to your team’s calendar. This way you never forget to staff an event properly.</p>\n<p>For those that can’t volunteer, but want to support your cause, just add a payment option to your volunteer form so they can donate.</p>\n<h3>3. Program Registrations</h3>\n<p>If your nonprofit offers help to those in need, like Love Your Brain does, consider adding a registration form to your website so people can sign up for the services you have available.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-273284\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/nonprofit-registration-example.png\" alt=\"nonprofit registration example\" width=\"562\" height=\"606\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/nonprofit-registration-example.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/nonprofit-registration-example-278x300.png 278w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>With a nonprofit registration form, you can gather important applicant information, vet applicants and choose those you want to accept, and easily manage all form entries in your WordPress dashboard to keep your programs and services running without a hitch.</p>\n<p>In addition, using any of the WPForms registration form templates, you can:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-clutter-free-forms-with-smart-logic/\">Use conditional logic</a> to take site visitors down the right registration path</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-multi-part-form-in-wordpress/\">Create multi-part forms</a> to fight form fatigue while collecting all required information</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-multiple-form-notifications-in-wordpress-forms/\">Create multiple form notifications</a> so you and your team receive the right information after forms are submitted</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-add-a-mailchimp-signup-checkbox-to-your-contact-form/\">Add a subscribe checkbox</a> to encourage people to sign up for future communication</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-multiple-form-confirmations-in-wpforms/\">Create multiple form confirmations</a> based on site visitor behavior</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Registration forms are not just for those who having paying customers that want to sign up for a program. Nonprofit organizations can offer their programs, free of charge, to those in need using the same type of form on their website.</p>\n<h3>4. Sponsorship Forms</h3>\n<p>Many nonprofits, such as the American Heart Association, rely on their big donors to sponsor events so they can continue to host them for the local community and those supporting their cause.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-273285\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/sponsorship-form-example.png\" alt=\"sponsorship form example\" width=\"562\" height=\"579\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/sponsorship-form-example.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/sponsorship-form-example-291x300.png 291w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>WPForms has a Sponsorship Request Form template that makes it easy for corporations to get in touch and let you know they want to help fund your cause.</p>\n<p>So, give people a way to promote their business, get involved with a good cause, and boost your annual fundraising total.</p>\n<p>In addition, you can let companies <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-file-upload-form-in-wordpress/\">upload an image file of their business logo</a>, pay their sponsorship fee right away, and <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-service-agreements-in-wordpress-with-digital-signatures/\">sign with an electronic signature</a> to ensure the validity of the donation using the WPForms <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/signature-addon/\">Signature addon</a>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-273288\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/electronic-signature-example.gif\" alt=\"electronic signature example\" width=\"562\" height=\"208\" /></p>\n<p>And there you have it! You now know how to use nonprofit WordPress forms to help your cause.</p>\n<p>If you need some additional ideas, check out this roundup of <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/online-fundraising-ideas-for-nonprofits/\">online fundraising ideas for nonprofit organizations</a>. And don’t forget to read up on <a href=\"http://optinmonster.com/beginners-guide-to-email-marketing/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">how to improve your email marketing efforts</a> so you can continue to build a bigger email list and reach a broader audience that wants to see your nonprofit succeed.</p>\n<p>So, what are you waiting for? Get started with the most powerful <a href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WordPress forms plugin</a> today.</p>\n<p>And don’t forget, if you like this article, then please follow us on <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/wpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Facebook</a> and <a href=\"http://twitter.com/easywpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Twitter</a>.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/unique-ways-to-use-nonprofit-wordpress-forms-to-help-your-cause/\">4 Unique Ways to Use Nonprofit WordPress Forms to Help Your Cause</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:89:\"https://wpforms.com/unique-ways-to-use-nonprofit-wordpress-forms-to-help-your-cause/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:6;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:51:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:59:\"How to Create a User Submitted Events Calendar in WordPress\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:73:\"https://wpforms.com/create-a-user-submitted-events-calendar-in-wordpress/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:82:\"https://wpforms.com/create-a-user-submitted-events-calendar-in-wordpress/#comments\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Mon, 17 Sep 2018 12:00:17 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:4:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:19:\"WordPress Tutorials\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:21:\"front end submissions\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:6:\"events\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:8:\"calendar\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:28:\"https://wpforms.com/?p=20715\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:585:\"<p>Do you want users to submit events to a calendar on your website? It can be a great time saver when you let your community help organize the events. In this article, we&#8217;ll show you how to create a user submitted events calendar in WordPress. Why Use an Event Submission Calendar? It&#8217;s helpful to have [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/create-a-user-submitted-events-calendar-in-wordpress/\">How to Create a User Submitted Events Calendar in WordPress</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:14:\"Lindsay Liedke\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:15096:\"<p>Do you want users to submit events to a calendar on your website? It can be a great time saver when you let your community help organize the events.</p>\n<p>In this article, we&#8217;ll show you how to create a user submitted events calendar in WordPress.</p>\n<h3>Why Use an Event Submission Calendar?</h3>\n<p>It&#8217;s helpful to have an events calendar on your website for displaying&#8230;</p>\n<ul>\n<li>local community events</li>\n<li>organization functions</li>\n<li>sales or specials</li>\n<li>sports matches</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&#8230;and many other types of events for site visitors to see and attend.</p>\n<p>Allowing your users to submit events instead of adding them all yourself is a great way to engage your audience and save yourself some time. You can even <a href=\"http://www.wpbeginner.com/beginners-guide/make-money-online\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">make money online</a> if you charge for event listings posted to your website&#8217;s calendar.</p>\n<p>Let&#8217;s take a look at an easy way to allow users to add their events to your site&#8217;s calendar.</p>\n<h3>Step 1: Create an Event Submission Form</h3>\n<p>The first thing you&#8217;ll need to do is install and activate the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/\">WPForms</a> plugin. Here’s a step by step guide on <a href=\"http://www.wpbeginner.com/beginners-guide/step-by-step-guide-to-install-a-wordpress-plugin-for-beginners/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">how to install a WordPress plugin</a>.</p>\n<p>Next, you’ll need to install and activate the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/post-submissions-addon/\">Post Submissions addon</a>.</p>\n<p>To do this, go to <strong>WPForms</strong> » <strong>Addon</strong> and find the one labeled <strong>Post Submissions</strong>.</p>\n<p>Click <strong>Install Addon</strong> and then <strong>Activate</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-235134\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/WPForms-Post-Submissions-Addon.png\" alt=\"WPForms Post Submissions Addon\" width=\"562\" height=\"193\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/WPForms-Post-Submissions-Addon.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/WPForms-Post-Submissions-Addon-300x103.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Now you’ll need to create a new form.</p>\n<p>Check out out tutorial on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-contact-form-in-wordpress/\">how to create a simple contact form</a> as an example to get started.</p>\n<p>Here&#8217;s what our form looks like:</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-272020\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/event-calendar-form.png\" alt=\"event calendar form\" width=\"562\" height=\"483\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/event-calendar-form.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/event-calendar-form-300x258.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>In our form, we added these fields to the simple contact form:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Event Title</strong> is a Single Line Text field</li>\n<li><strong>Start &amp; End Time</strong> are two Date/Time fields</li>\n<li><strong>Promotional Image</strong> is a File Upload field</li>\n</ul>\n<p>You can add additional fields by dragging them from the left hand panel to the right hand panel.</p>\n<p>Then, click on the field to make any changes. You can also click on a form field and drag it to rearrange the order on your user registration form.</p>\n<p>If you don&#8217;t want to customize a simple contact form, you might look into using the Event Planner Form template found in the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/features/form-templates/\">Form Templates Pack addon</a>. This template comes with many of the form fields your site visitors will need to fill out to submit their event to your calendar.</p>\n<p>If you decide you want to monetize your website, and charge users to submit their event on your calendar, read this documentation on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-allow-users-to-choose-a-payment-method-on-your-form/\">how to allow users to choose a payment method</a> on your WordPress forms.</p>\n<p>Click <strong>Save</strong>.</p>\n<h3>Step 2: Create a Calendar</h3>\n<p>Next, you&#8217;ll need to create a calendar for users to add their events to. For this, you can use <a title=\"The Events Calendar plugin in WordPress Repository\" href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/the-events-calendar/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">The Events Calendar</a>. This is a free plugin for WordPress websites.</p>\n<p>To do this, go to <strong>Plugins</strong> » <strong>Add New </strong>in your WordPress dashboard and search for &#8220;The Events Calendar&#8221; plugin.</p>\n<p>Click <strong>Install Now </strong>and then <strong>Activate</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-272014\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/the-events-calendar-plugin.png\" alt=\"the events calendar plugin\" width=\"562\" height=\"419\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/the-events-calendar-plugin.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/the-events-calendar-plugin-300x224.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>The Events Calendar is now ready for you to use.</p>\n<p>This plugin will create a <a title=\"how to create custom post types in WordPress\" href=\"http://www.wpbeginner.com/wp-tutorials/how-to-create-custom-post-types-in-wordpress/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">custom post type</a> called <strong>Events </strong>that will appear in your WordPress dashboard. Custom post types work the same way that posts and pages work. The Events custom post type will, however, remain separate from your site&#8217;s posts and pages.</p>\n<p>You can preview the calendar that is created after installing and activating the plugin at <code>http://yoursite.com/events</code>.</p>\n<p>For now, it won&#8217;t show much information since you don&#8217;t have any events submitted yet.</p>\n<h3>Step 3: Connect Your Form to Your Calendar</h3>\n<p>After setting up The Events Calendar plugin, you need to connect the form you&#8217;ve created to your calendar.</p>\n<p>To start, go to <strong>Settings » Post Submissions </strong>in the form editor and turn post submissions <strong>On.</strong></p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-272015\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/turn-post-submissions-on.png\" alt=\"turn post submissions on\" width=\"562\" height=\"260\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/turn-post-submissions-on.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/turn-post-submissions-on-300x139.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Next, you&#8217;ll want to match each field to the relevant part of the event custom post type.</p>\n<p>In our example we chose:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Event Title for the <strong>Post Title </strong>dropdown</li>\n<li>Description for the <strong>Post Content </strong>dropdown</li>\n<li>Promotional Image for the <strong>Post Featured Image </strong>dropdown</li>\n</ul>\n<p>We also set <strong>Post Type</strong> to Events (the custom post type created by enabling The Events Calendar plugin), and <strong>Post Status</strong> to Pending Review so that you can approve each submission before it goes live on your site.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-272012\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/post-submissions-settings.png\" alt=\"post submissions settings\" width=\"562\" height=\"398\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/post-submissions-settings.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/post-submissions-settings-300x212.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Now you can scroll down to the <strong>Custom Post Meta</strong> section.</p>\n<p>The last part of connecting your form to the calendar is to add just a bit of code here. This will connect the start and end times in your form to the start and end times in the calendar.</p>\n<p>We&#8217;ve shown you the code you need to include in the image below, but you can look up any other <a title=\"Events Calendar PRO WordPress post meta data\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/knowledgebase/wordpress-post-meta-data/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">custom meta code</a> that The Events Calendar offers if you want to customize your calendar even more.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-272019\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/the-events-calendar-custom-meta.png\" alt=\"the events calendar custom meta\" width=\"562\" height=\"218\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/the-events-calendar-custom-meta.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/the-events-calendar-custom-meta-300x116.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Click <strong>Save</strong>.</p>\n<h3>Step 4: Customize the Thank You Message</h3>\n<p>Before you publish your event submission form, it&#8217;s a good idea to change the default thank you message users will see.</p>\n<p>You can do this by going to <strong>Settings » Confirmation</strong>. In the preview panel, customize your message in any way you like.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-272018\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/customize-confirmation-message.png\" alt=\"customize confirmation message\" width=\"562\" height=\"310\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/customize-confirmation-message.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/customize-confirmation-message-300x165.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>You can also send users to a designated thank you page or a separate website altogether after they&#8217;ve submitted an event to your website&#8217;s calendar.</p>\n<p>For help with these type of form confirmations, check out this helpful documentation on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/setup-form-confirmation-wpforms/\">how to set up form confirmations in WordPress</a>.</p>\n<p>For inspiration, you can also check out these helpful articles:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/4-thank-you-page-examples-to-boost-customer-loyalty/\">Effective Thank You page examples</a> that will boost user loyalty</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/form-success-message-ideas-to-boost-customer-happiness/\">Great success messages</a> you can display for site visitors</li>\n</ul>\n<p>For help with customizing multiple confirmation messages, check out <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-multiple-form-confirmations-in-wpforms/\">how to create multiple form confirmations in WPForms</a>.</p>\n<h3>Step 5: Publish Your User Submitted Events Form</h3>\n<p>WPForms allows you to add your forms to many locations on your website, including your blog posts, pages, and even <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-add-a-contact-form-in-wordpress-sidebar-widget/\">sidebar widgets</a>.</p>\n<p>Let’s take a look at the most common post/page embed option.</p>\n<p>To start, create a new post or page in WordPress and then click on the <strong>Add Form</strong> button.</p>\n<p>Next, select your contact form in the modal popup and click <strong>Add Form</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-272017\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/add-user-submitted-events-form.png\" alt=\"add user submitted events form\" width=\"562\" height=\"332\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/add-user-submitted-events-form.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/add-user-submitted-events-form-300x177.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Then, publish your post or page so your form will appear on your website and users can begin submitting their events.</p>\n<h3>Step 6: Review and Publish Event Submissions</h3>\n<p>After your form is live on your site, you just need to approve the events users submit. To do this, go to <strong>Events</strong> in the WordPress dashboard.</p>\n<p>You&#8217;ll see that any submitted events will be listed as <strong>Pending</strong>. This means they need to be approved by you before they appear on your site&#8217;s calendar.</p>\n<p>Click <strong>Edit</strong> underneath the event title.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-272013\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/review-event-submission.png\" alt=\"review event submission\" width=\"562\" height=\"366\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/review-event-submission.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/review-event-submission-300x195.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Preview the submission, taking special note of the <strong>Time &amp; Date</strong> near the bottom of your screen. This will be the time listed on your calendar.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-272024\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/event-calendar-time.png\" alt=\"event calendar time\" width=\"562\" height=\"241\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/event-calendar-time.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/event-calendar-time-300x129.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>When you&#8217;re finished reviewing all the event details, click <strong>Publish</strong>. Then you can view your events calendar at <code>http://yoursite.com/events</code>.</p>\n<p>When the user hovers their mouse over the calendar event, they&#8217;ll see a preview popup. By clicking on it, they&#8217;ll get the full event listing.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-272025\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/example-calendar-submission.png\" alt=\"example calendar submission\" width=\"562\" height=\"343\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/example-calendar-submission.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/example-calendar-submission-300x183.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>And there you have it! You now know how to create a user submitted events calendar in WordPress using WPForms.</p>\n<p>Do you want to allow clients to schedule appointments on your work calendar? You might also want to check out our guide on <a title=\"How to Create a Client Booking Form in WordPress\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-client-booking-form-in-wordpress/\">how to create a client booking form</a>.</p>\n<p>So, what are you waiting for? Get started with the most powerful <a href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WordPress forms plugin</a> today.</p>\n<p>And don’t forget, if you like this article, then please follow us on <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/wpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Facebook</a> and <a href=\"http://twitter.com/easywpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Twitter</a>.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/create-a-user-submitted-events-calendar-in-wordpress/\">How to Create a User Submitted Events Calendar in WordPress</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:78:\"https://wpforms.com/create-a-user-submitted-events-calendar-in-wordpress/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:2:\"34\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:7;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:54:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:57:\"How to Send a PDF Attachment in a Form Notification Email\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:78:\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-send-a-pdf-attachment-in-a-form-notification-email/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:86:\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-send-a-pdf-attachment-in-a-form-notification-email/#respond\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Thu, 13 Sep 2018 12:00:49 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:5:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:19:\"WordPress Tutorials\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:17:\"form notification\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:18:\"email notification\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:15:\"lead generation\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:4;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:11:\"lead magnet\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:29:\"https://wpforms.com/?p=270034\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:569:\"<p>Want to learn how to send a PDF attachment in a form notification email? Being able to send PDFs to site visitors after they’ve subscribed is one of the easiest ways to deliver the lead magnet you promised in exchange for an email address. In this article, we’ll show you how to send a PDF [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-send-a-pdf-attachment-in-a-form-notification-email/\">How to Send a PDF Attachment in a Form Notification Email</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:14:\"Lindsay Liedke\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:11817:\"<p>Want to learn how to send a PDF attachment in a form notification email? Being able to send PDFs to site visitors after they’ve subscribed is one of the easiest ways to deliver the lead magnet you promised in exchange for an email address.</p>\n<p>In this article, we’ll show you how to send a PDF in a form notification email using WPForms.</p>\n<h3>Why Offer Lead Magnets?</h3>\n<p>Lead magnets are one of the best ways to build your email list. Used as an <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/10-research-based-tips-to-improve-contact-form-conversions/\">incentive to get people to subscribe</a>, lead magnets are pieces of high-quality content you can deliver once they successfully sign up.</p>\n<p>Good lead magnets are valuable enough for people to want to sign up for your email list and continue to receive marketing materials from you in the future.</p>\n<p>Some of the most common lead magnets include PDFs in the form of:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>eBooks</li>\n<li>Checklists</li>\n<li>Reports</li>\n<li>Case Studies</li>\n<li>Templates</li>\n<li>Resource Lists</li>\n<li>Guides</li>\n<li>Infographics</li>\n<li>And so much more</li>\n</ul>\n<p><a href=\"http://optinmonster.com/beginners-guide-to-email-marketing/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Email marketing is critical</a> if you want to grow your readership or customer base. It’s the best way to communicate with people that are interested in what you have to offer. Plus, you own your email list and have complete control over it at all times.</p>\n<p>Not to mention, email marketing is known for <a href=\"https://www.lyfemarketing.com/blog/email-marketing-roi/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">having the highest ROI</a> when compared to digital marketing strategies like SEO and advertisements.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-270036\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/email-marketing-roi.png\" alt=\"email marketing roi\" width=\"562\" height=\"287\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/email-marketing-roi.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/email-marketing-roi-300x153.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>So, let’s see how to can send your lead magnet to new subscribers in the WPForms email notification.</p>\n<h3>Step 1: Create a lead Magnet</h3>\n<p>The first thing you’ll need to do is create a lead magnet for your subscribe form.</p>\n<p>If you need some inspiration, you can always check out this <a href=\"https://optinmonster.com/9-lead-magnets-to-increase-subscribers/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">roundup of highly effective lead magnet ideas</a> to help you grow your email list. Though not all of them will be PDFs you can offer, there are plenty of options to choose from.</p>\n<p>Once you’ve created your PDF lead magnet, upload it to your WordPress website.</p>\n<p>To do this, go to <strong>Media</strong> » <strong>Add New</strong> and upload it to your site like you would an image.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-173487\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/Media-Library.png\" alt=\"Media Library\" width=\"562\" height=\"248\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/Media-Library.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/Media-Library-300x132.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>If the PDF attachment you’re creating is duplicating any content that is already on your website, you might want to hide it from Google so you don’t get penalized in search rankings for having duplicate content. You also don’t want the lead magnet to rank higher than the original piece of content.</p>\n<p>To hide your lead magnet from Google, you can use the robots.txt file of your site to make sure Google doens&#8217;t index it.</p>\n<p>For example, let’s say you’re offering site visitors a PDF version of a blog post and it has a URL that looks like this: http://example.com/2018/12/printable.pdf.</p>\n<p>To hide it from search engines, here is how you’ll add this URL to your robots.txt file.</p>\n<p><code>User-agent: *<br />\nDisallow: /2018/12/printable.pdf</code></p>\n<p>For more help with this step, read up on <a href=\"http://www.wpbeginner.com/wp-tutorials/how-to-hide-a-wordpress-page-from-google/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">how to hide pages from Google</a>.</p>\n<h3>Step 2: Create a New WordPress Form</h3>\n<p>To create a new WordPress form, you’ll need to install and activate the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/pricing/\">WPForms plugin</a>. For more details, see this step by step guide on <a title=\"Step by step guide on How to Install a WordPress Plugin\" href=\"http://www.wpbeginner.com/beginners-guide/step-by-step-guide-to-install-a-wordpress-plugin-for-beginners/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">how to install a plugin in WordPress</a>.</p>\n<p>Next, you’ll need to create a signup form. For help with this step, see our tutorial on <a href=\" https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-mailchimp-subscribe-form-in-wordpress/\">how to create a MailChimp subscribe form</a> as an example to get started.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-207966\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/Newsletter-Signup-Form-Preview.png\" alt=\"Newsletter Signup Form Preview\" width=\"562\" height=\"348\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/Newsletter-Signup-Form-Preview.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/Newsletter-Signup-Form-Preview-300x186.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Keep in mind, you can create many types of forms with the WPForms plugin templates:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-file-upload-form-in-wordpress/\">File upload forms</a> to gather additional information from site visitors</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-job-application-form-in-wordpress/\">Job application forms</a> to fill an open position that’s available</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/create-a-survey-form-in-wordpress-step-by-step/\">Survey forms</a> to gather customer feedback about your business</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-user-registration-form-in-wordpress/\">User registration forms</a> so people can sign up for subscriptions, services, or other plans</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-nonprofit-donation-form/\">Donation forms</a> so you can collect money for your cause or organization</li>\n<li>And any number of subscribe forms using our <a href=\"http://www.wpbeginner.com/showcase/best-email-marketing-services/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">email service provider</a> integrations: <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/mailchimp-addon/\">MailChimp</a>, <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/aweber-addon/\">AWeber</a>, <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/features/constant-contact/\">Constant Contact</a>, <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/campaign-monitor-addon/\">Campaign Monitor</a>, <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/drip-addon/\">Drip</a>, and <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/getresponse-addon/\">GetResponse</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>All of these forms, and the hundred more you can create with the WPForms <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/features/form-templates/\">Form Templates addon</a>, can have a <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-add-an-aweber-signup-checkbox-to-your-contact-form/\">signup checkbox added to them</a> to encourage people to subscribe to your email list in exchange for a lead magnet.</p>\n<p>Just make sure that the form you create includes details about the lead magnet people will receive if they sign up.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-173490\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/Content-Upgrade-Newsletter-Form.png\" alt=\"Content Upgrade Newsletter Form\" width=\"562\" height=\"376\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/Content-Upgrade-Newsletter-Form.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/Content-Upgrade-Newsletter-Form-300x201.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<h3>Step 3: Add the PDF to Your Form’s Notification Email</h3>\n<p>To add your PDF lead magnet to your form’s notification email, first go to <strong>Media</strong> » <strong>Library</strong> and find the PDF attachment you uploaded to your website that will serve as your lead magnet.</p>\n<p>Then, copy the lead magnet’s URL.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-270038\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/pdf-in-media-library.png\" alt=\"pdf in media library\" width=\"562\" height=\"414\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/pdf-in-media-library.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/pdf-in-media-library-300x221.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Next, go to <strong>Settings</strong> » <strong>Notifications</strong> in the form editor.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-270037\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/form-notification-settings.png\" alt=\"form notification settings\" width=\"562\" height=\"344\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/form-notification-settings.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/form-notification-settings-300x184.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Then, in the <strong>Message</strong> section, paste this HTML, complete with the URL of your PDF and the text you want for the link:</p>\n<p>&lt;a href=&#8221;COPIEDURL&#8221; target=&#8221;_blank&#8221;&gt;Text for link&lt;/a&gt;</p>\n<p>So, for our example, our notification’s message section will look like this:</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-270035\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/add-pdf-attachment-to-notification-email.png\" alt=\"add pdf attachment to notification email\" width=\"562\" height=\"369\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/add-pdf-attachment-to-notification-email.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/add-pdf-attachment-to-notification-email-300x197.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Click <strong>Save</strong>.</p>\n<p>Now, any time someone fills out your signup form and subscribes, they will receive a notification email from you that includes the lead magnet you promised them for subscribing.</p>\n<p>And there you have it! You now know how to send a PDF attachment in a form notification email to people when they sign up for your email list.</p>\n<p>If you find that your email notifications aren’t delivering the way they’re supposed to, be sure to read up on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-fix-wordpress-contact-form-not-sending-email-issue/\">how to get WordPress from notifications using the WP Mail SMTP plugin</a> so that you know every site visitor that subscribes to your email list gets their lead magnet.</p>\n<p>And if you want to learn how to create a lead magnet and send it in a marketing email or add it to your form’s confirmation messages, check out this helpful tutorial on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-simple-lead-magnet-optin-form-in-wordpress/\">how to create a simple lead magnet optin form in WordPress</a>.</p>\n<p>So, what are you waiting for? Get started with the most powerful <a href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WordPress forms plugin</a> today.</p>\n<p>And don’t forget, if you like this article, then please follow us on <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/wpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Facebook</a> and <a href=\"http://twitter.com/easywpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Twitter</a>.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-send-a-pdf-attachment-in-a-form-notification-email/\">How to Send a PDF Attachment in a Form Notification Email</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:83:\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-send-a-pdf-attachment-in-a-form-notification-email/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:8;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:51:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:53:\"Top 6 Places to Include a Contact Form for More Leads\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:73:\"https://wpforms.com/top-places-to-include-a-contact-form-on-your-website/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:81:\"https://wpforms.com/top-places-to-include-a-contact-form-on-your-website/#respond\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Tue, 11 Sep 2018 12:00:12 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:4:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:19:\"WordPress Tutorials\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:12:\"contact form\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:20:\"form conversion rate\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:15:\"lead generation\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:28:\"https://wpforms.com/?p=17239\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:581:\"<p>Are you making it easy for your website visitors to reach you? By placing your contact form in prominent places on your site, you&#8217;ll get more inquiries from your visitors. In this article, we’ll show you the top 6 places to include a contact form on your website for more leads. Increase Leads with Contact [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/top-places-to-include-a-contact-form-on-your-website/\">Top 6 Places to Include a Contact Form for More Leads</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:14:\"Lindsay Liedke\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:12175:\"<p>Are you making it easy for your website visitors to reach you? By placing your contact form in prominent places on your site, you&#8217;ll get more inquiries from your visitors.</p>\n<p>In this article, we’ll show you the top 6 places to include a contact form on your website for more leads.</p>\n<h3>Increase Leads with Contact Forms</h3>\n<p>Every page on your website needs a way to guide visitors through the process toward becoming happy customers, no matter what industry you are in. Whether you are&#8230;</p>\n<ul>\n<li>A blogger seeking speaking opportunities</li>\n<li>A business owner seeking customers</li>\n<li>An e-commerce store increasing sales</li>\n<li>A non-profit organizer fostering donor relations</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&#8230;it&#8217;s important to encourage visitors to take the first step in their <a href=\"https://optinmonster.com/roadmap-to-capturing-leads-throughout-the-customer-journey/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">customer journey</a>.</p>\n<p>To help your website visitors get started, you&#8217;ll need a call to action on each page. This is some sort of prompt that will encourage a visitor to take action toward becoming a client, such as joining your <a title=\"Beginner\'s Guide to Email Marketing\" href=\"http://optinmonster.com/beginners-guide-to-email-marketing/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">email newsletter</a> or downloading a <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-deliver-a-content-upgrade-to-form-subscribers-step-by-step/\">an enticing content upgrade</a>.</p>\n<p>But, how can you include a call to action on your blog&#8217;s posts and pages? And how will this help you <a title=\"Exit Popup Hacks That Will Grow Your Subscribers and Revenue\" href=\"http://optinmonster.com/40-exit-popup-hacks-that-will-grow-your-subscribers-and-revenue/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">get more leads</a>?</p>\n<p>Well, there’s a simple solution: by <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-simple-contact-form-in-wordpress/\">creating a simple contact form</a>.</p>\n<p>Here are 6 places to include a contact form on your website so you can start gathering more leads.</p>\n<h3>1. In Your Sidebar</h3>\n<p>By placing a contact form in the sidebar of your site, it will be easily accessible no matter where visitors are in your site, including your blog posts. Your form can appear on the left or right side of the website like this:</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-5163 size-full\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/contact-form-sidebar-widget.jpg\" alt=\"Get more leads with a Contact Form Sidebar Widget\" width=\"363\" height=\"502\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/contact-form-sidebar-widget.jpg 363w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/contact-form-sidebar-widget-217x300.jpg 217w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 363px) 100vw, 363px\" /></p>\n<p>Need help placing WordPress contact form widget? See our tutorial: <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-add-a-contact-form-in-wordpress-sidebar-widget/\">how to add a contact form in a WordPress sidebar widget</a>.</p>\n<h3>2. About Page</h3>\n<p>An often overlooked opportunity to connect with your visitors is on your about page. To make the most of this page, remember to include these details:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>What your business does</strong> using plain language.</li>\n<li><strong>What <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-testimonials-from-wordpress-form-submissions/\">happy customers are saying </a></strong>about their experiences with you.</li>\n<li><strong>Who works at your company</strong> and how to reach each person.</li>\n<li><strong>A story</strong> about how your products and services impact people.</li>\n<li><strong>A call-to-action</strong> that motivates visitors to do something now, such as a contact form.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>To see an example of an outstanding About Page, check out <a href=\"http://blakesuarez.com/contact\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Blake Suarez’s website</a>. The page builds trust, introduces the site owner, tells a story, and ends with a contact form.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-265232\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/about-us-contact-form-example.png\" alt=\"about us contact form example\" width=\"562\" height=\"382\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/about-us-contact-form-example.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/about-us-contact-form-example-300x204.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<h3>3. Contact Page</h3>\n<p>Your contact page is one of the most important pages on your website. People visiting it are more likely to do business with you.</p>\n<p>To help your visitor take their next step toward becoming a happy customer, be sure to:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Spell out <em>why</em> someone should contact you</strong> and how you can help solve their needs.</li>\n<li><strong>List your phone number</strong> for visitors that prefer to be supported by calling someone.</li>\n<li><strong>Link to social media accounts</strong> like Twitter, Facebook, and Instagram to give visitors a way to engage with the business.</li>\n<li><strong>Include a short form</strong> using fields that will help you understand who&#8217;s contacting you <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-build-spam-free-wordpress-contact-forms-the-ultimate-guide/\">without getting spammed</a></li>\n<li><strong>Redirect visitors to a <a title=\"How to Redirect Users after WordPress Form Submission\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-redirect-users-after-wordpress-form-submit/\">thank-you page</a></strong> that explains when and how you&#8217;ll be contacting them.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>If you make it easy for your visitors to reach you using the tips above, like <a href=\"https://www.pixpa.com/contact-us\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Pixpa</a> does in the example below, you&#8217;ll notice an increase in the number of leads you gather.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-265235\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/contact-us-page-example.png\" alt=\"contact us page example\" width=\"562\" height=\"446\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/contact-us-page-example.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/contact-us-page-example-300x238.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<h3>4. Above the Fold…or Below</h3>\n<p>There is a long-standing debate over whether you should place your contact form above or below the fold on your website’s homepage. And the truth is, each website will benefit from one or the other, depending on the target audience.</p>\n<p>According to a <a href=\"https://www.nngroup.com/articles/page-fold-manifesto/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">study conducted by Nielsen Norman Group</a>, content placed above the fold was seen by site visitors 102% more times than anything placed below the fold.</p>\n<p>So, adding a contact form to your site like <a href=\"https://paravelinc.com/contact/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Paravel</a> does will definitely get you action on your contact form since it&#8217;s well above the fold.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-265233\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/above-the-fold-example.png\" alt=\"above the fold example\" width=\"562\" height=\"471\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/above-the-fold-example.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/above-the-fold-example-300x251.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>That said, there is the notion that people who scroll do so for a reason.</p>\n<p>People scrolling down webpages are showing interest in what you have to offer, and because of this, are probably more likely to fill out and submit a contact form on your site, even if it appears below the fold.</p>\n<p>Take for instance <a href=\"http://melonfree.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Melonfree Web Consulting</a>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-265234\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/below-the-fold-example.png\" alt=\"below the fold example\" width=\"562\" height=\"551\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/below-the-fold-example.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/below-the-fold-example-300x294.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Users must scroll all the way to the bottom of the page to access the contact form. However, along the way, users are viewing information about their services, learning why Melonfree is the company to go with, and even have access to a portfolio of past work.</p>\n<p>The idea with this is, if users get that far down a webpage, and realize they need to get in touch after learning all about your business, they will.</p>\n<h3>5. After Blog Posts</h3>\n<p>Following the thinking mentioned above when it comes to placing contact forms below the fold on your site’s homepage, you might consider adding one below your site’s blog content.</p>\n<p>Again, someone that gets through an entire blog post, whether in full or by scanning what you’ve written, is going to do one of two things:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Leave your site forever because they didn’t like what you wrote and have no intention of ever returning</li>\n<li>Or the more likely scenario, which is either opt to get in touch with you or continue to read more of your site’s content, opting to fill out your form when they are all done</li>\n</ol>\n<p>If you can hook readers with your site content, and want to give them a chance to contact you when they’ve seen what you have to offer, do so immediately following a blog post with a simple contact form.</p>\n<h3>6. The Footer Section</h3>\n<p>Lots of people scroll to the bottom of websites looking for more information. In fact, a lot of people look for social media icons, an About Us page, maps of physical store locations, and you guessed it, contact information.</p>\n<p>Rather than have site visitors navigate to a separate contact page, simplify the process for those that may be on the fence about your business in the first place.</p>\n<p>For inspiration, check out <a href=\"https://groverwebdesign.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Grover Web Design’s footer section</a>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-265236\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/footer-section-example.png\" alt=\"footer section example\" width=\"562\" height=\"429\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/footer-section-example.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/footer-section-example-300x229.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Not only do they include a short contact form, they have their company’s physical address, phone number, and social media icons, which is exactly what people are looking for when they scroll to the footer of any website.</p>\n<p>If you need help doing this with WPForms, check out our step by step tutorial on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-add-a-contact-form-to-your-wordpress-footer/\">how to add a contact form to your WordPress footer</a>.</p>\n<p>And there you have it! 6 excellent places to put a contact form on your website so people can get in touch with you any time they need to.</p>\n<p>Want to do even more with your contact forms? Check out <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-contact-form-popup-in-wordpress/\">how to create a contact from popup in WordPress</a> so you can add a contact form anywhere on your website.</p>\n<p>So, what are you waiting for? Get started with the most powerful <a href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WordPress forms plugin</a> today.</p>\n<p>And don’t forget, if you like this article, then please follow us on <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/wpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Facebook</a> and <a href=\"http://twitter.com/easywpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Twitter</a>.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/top-places-to-include-a-contact-form-on-your-website/\">Top 6 Places to Include a Contact Form for More Leads</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:78:\"https://wpforms.com/top-places-to-include-a-contact-form-on-your-website/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:9;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:51:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:52:\"How to Create Multiple Form Confirmations in WPForms\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:73:\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-multiple-form-confirmations-in-wpforms/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:81:\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-multiple-form-confirmations-in-wpforms/#respond\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Mon, 10 Sep 2018 12:00:57 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:4:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:19:\"WordPress Tutorials\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:17:\"form confirmation\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:17:\"conditional logic\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:25:\"conditional confirmations\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:29:\"https://wpforms.com/?p=267109\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:607:\"<p>Do you want to learn how to create multiple form confirmations in WPForms? Being able to send customized form confirmations to people filling out your WordPress forms improves the user experience. In this article, we’ll show you how to set up several form confirmations for one WordPress form based on user behavior using smart conditional [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-multiple-form-confirmations-in-wpforms/\">How to Create Multiple Form Confirmations in WPForms</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:14:\"Lindsay Liedke\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:12693:\"<p>Do you want to learn how to create multiple form confirmations in WPForms? Being able to send customized form confirmations to people filling out your WordPress forms improves the user experience.</p>\n<p>In this article, we’ll show you how to set up several form confirmations for one WordPress form based on user behavior using smart conditional logic.</p>\n<h3>Step 1: Create a New WordPress Form</h3>\n<p>The first thing you’ll need to do is install and activate the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/pricing/\">WPForms plugin</a>. For more details, see this step by step guide on <a title=\"Step by step guide on How to Install a WordPress Plugin\" href=\"http://www.wpbeginner.com/beginners-guide/step-by-step-guide-to-install-a-wordpress-plugin-for-beginners/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">how to install a plugin in WordPress</a>.</p>\n<p>Next, you’ll need to create a WordPress contact form. For help with this step, check out our helpful tutorial on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-simple-contact-form-in-wordpress/\">how to create a simple contact form in WordPress</a>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-218831\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Simple-Contact-Form.png\" alt=\"Simple Contact Form\" width=\"562\" height=\"372\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Simple-Contact-Form.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Simple-Contact-Form-300x199.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Keep in mind, you can create many different types of forms using the pre-designed WPForms templates:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-simple-order-form-in-wordpress/\">Simple order forms</a> that accept payments directly from customers</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-file-upload-form-in-wordpress/\">File upload forms</a> to gather additional information from site visitors</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-job-application-form-in-wordpress/\">Job application forms</a> to fill an open position that’s available</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/create-a-survey-form-in-wordpress-step-by-step/\">Survey forms</a> to gather customer feedback about your business</li>\n<li>And any number of subscribe forms using our <a href=\"http://www.wpbeginner.com/showcase/best-email-marketing-services/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">email service provider</a> integrations: <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/mailchimp-addon/\">MailChimp</a>, <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/aweber-addon/\">Aweber</a>, <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/features/constant-contact/\">Constant Contact</a>, <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/campaign-monitor-addon/\">Campaign Monitor</a>, <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/drip-addon/\">Drip</a>, and <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/getresponse-addon/\">GetResponse</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-nonprofit-donation-form/\">Donation forms</a> that collect payment to support your organization and your cause</li>\n</ul>\n<p>All of these forms, and the hundred more you can create with the WPForms <a title=\"How to Install and Use the Stripe Addon with WPForms\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-install-and-use-the-stripe-addon-with-wpforms/\">Form Templates addon</a>, can display multiple confirmations based on how users fill out your form.</p>\n<h3>Step 2: Customize Your WordPress Form</h3>\n<p>WPForms makes customizing your forms, no matter which kind they are, very simple to do.</p>\n<p>You can add additional form fields to your form by dragging them from the left hand panel to the right hand panel. You can also customize the fields by clicking on the field.</p>\n<p>In our example, we’re going to <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-user-registration-form-in-wordpress/\">create a user registration form</a> that does one of two things after a person clicks submit:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Display a thank you message for registering and customize the confirmation to explain to the user what the steps are</li>\n<li>Redirect users to the login page so they can immediately log in to their account</li>\n</ol>\n<p>To do this, we’ll ask registered users if they want to sign in right after registering.</p>\n<p>Our form will look something like this:</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-267118\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/user-registration-form-example.png\" alt=\"user registration form example\" width=\"562\" height=\"448\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/user-registration-form-example.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/user-registration-form-example-300x239.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Now we’re ready to set up our two confirmations.</p>\n<h3>Step 3: Choose Your Notification Type</h3>\n<p>Before you create multiple form confirmations for your forms, you’ll need to decide which confirmation types you want to use.</p>\n<p>WPForms has three different types of form confirmations to choose from:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Message:</strong> Display a default thank you message to site visitors when they submit your form. Or, customize the message to read however you like. Here are some <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/form-success-message-ideas-to-boost-customer-happiness/\">effective thank you messages</a> you can use on your form’s message confirmations. You can also <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-simple-lead-magnet-optin-form-in-wordpress/\">provide users the lead magnet you promised</a> them in exchange for subscribing here, instead of making them wait for it to arrive in their email.</li>\n<li><strong>Show Page:</strong> Redirect people to a page on your website, such as a thank you page, once they’ve submitted a form on your website. For help with this step, check how to <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/4-thank-you-page-examples-to-boost-customer-loyalty/\">these Thank You page examples</a>.</li>\n<li><strong>Go to URL (Redirect):</strong> This option is for those times you want to redirect users to a different website after submitting your form.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>If you want to use one confirmation type for all site visitors that submit a form on your site, check out this helpful guide on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/setup-form-confirmation-wpforms/#message\">setting up form confirmations in WPForms</a>.</p>\n<p>However, if you’re here because you want to set up more than one confirmation for a single WordPress form, keep reading.</p>\n<p>Remember, for our example, we’re going to use the message and show page confirmation types.</p>\n<h3>Step 4: Create Multiple Form Confirmations in WPForms</h3>\n<p>To start, go to <strong>Settings</strong> » <strong>Confirmations</strong> in the form editor.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-267115\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/form-confirmation-settings.png\" alt=\"form confirmation settings\" width=\"562\" height=\"415\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/form-confirmation-settings.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/form-confirmation-settings-300x222.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Notice the default message confirmation displaying.</p>\n<p>To change this default message to thank your site visitor for registering, and to explain the next steps, click in the text box and make your changes.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-267116\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/message-confirmation.png\" alt=\"message confirmation\" width=\"562\" height=\"459\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/message-confirmation.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/message-confirmation-300x245.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>This confirmation will be the one people see when they select “No” to the question “Would you like to sign in immediately following registration?”</p>\n<p>Next, we will configure our second confirmation for those that <strong>do want to sign in right after registering</strong>.</p>\n<p>To do this, click the <strong>Add New Confirmation</strong> button on the default confirmation.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-267110\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/add-new-confirmation.png\" alt=\"add new confirmation\" width=\"562\" height=\"348\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/add-new-confirmation.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/add-new-confirmation-300x186.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Next, enter a confirmation name. This is for your use only so name it anything you like.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-267112\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/confirmation-name.png\" alt=\"confirmation name\" width=\"562\" height=\"330\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/confirmation-name.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/confirmation-name-300x176.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Click <strong>OK</strong>.</p>\n<p>Now you’ll select the type of confirmation you want this one to be. In our example, we’ll choose <strong>Show Page</strong> from the dropdown menu.</p>\n<p>We’ll also choose which page on our website we want people to be directed to once they register, which in this case is the <strong>Login</strong> page.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-267117\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/second-confirmation-type.png\" alt=\"second confirmation type\" width=\"562\" height=\"376\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/second-confirmation-type.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/second-confirmation-type-300x201.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<h3>Step 5: Enable Conditional Logic</h3>\n<p>Now that you have your second form confirmation set up, it’s time to enable conditional logic to make sure that when people submit your form, they see the right confirmation based on their behavior.</p>\n<p>Underneath the Confirmation Type and Confirmation Page dropdown menus, click the <strong>Enable conditional logic</strong> box.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-267114\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/enable-conditional-logic.png\" alt=\"enable conditional logic\" width=\"562\" height=\"376\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/enable-conditional-logic.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/enable-conditional-logic-300x201.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>When you do, you’ll be able to set your conditional rule.</p>\n<p>For our example, we’ll set the conditional logic to display this confirmation type if the question “Would you like to sign immediately following registration?” is “Yes.”</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-267111\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/conditional-logic-rule.png\" alt=\"conditional logic rule\" width=\"562\" height=\"237\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/conditional-logic-rule.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/conditional-logic-rule-300x127.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>This way, anyone that clicks “Yes” will automatically be directed to the Login page on our website.</p>\n<p>And there you have it! You now know how to create multiple form confirmations in WPForms. You can follow these same steps and add as many different confirmations for your forms as you’d like, making WPForms the most flexible, <strong>yet beginner friendly</strong>, contact form builder available today.</p>\n<p>If you’re looking for other ways to utilize smart logic on your WordPress forms, make sure to check out these <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/inspiring-uses-of-conditional-logic-to-boost-form-conversions/\">3 inspiring uses of conditional logic to boost form conversions</a>.</p>\n<p>So, what are you waiting for? Get started with the most powerful <a href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WordPress forms plugin</a> today.</p>\n<p>And don’t forget, if you like this article, then please follow us on <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/wpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Facebook</a> and <a href=\"http://twitter.com/easywpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Twitter</a>.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-multiple-form-confirmations-in-wpforms/\">How to Create Multiple Form Confirmations in WPForms</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:78:\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-multiple-form-confirmations-in-wpforms/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}}}s:27:\"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom\";a:1:{s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s: